<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="529" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,1079]" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,910,935]" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin “sinuosus”, meaning “sinuous, curved”, and refers to the long and sinuous setae on sternite 5, epandrium and cercal plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="529" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,151,1079]" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,982,1007]" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">Remarks.</emphasis>
In Emden’s (1951) key to 
<taxonomicName box="[623,761,983,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[623,761,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">Limnophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the new species runs to 
<taxonomicName box="[1052,1178,983,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptopus">
<emphasis box="[1052,1178,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">L. leptopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Seguy" authorityName="Seguy" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stragula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="529">L. stragula</emphasis>
(Séguy))
</taxonomicName>
, because of the presence of 2 posterior preapicals on mid femur and the absence of the lower katepisternal seta, but the general appearance of both species is totally different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
